## Quick start

```bash
# 1. Clone this repo
git clone <repo-url>
cd <repo-dir>

# 2. Authenticate with <Tool Name> (if not already done)
<do-auth-command>        # completes OAuth / login flow
<check-auth-command>     # verify: exit 0 = authenticated

# 3. Run the installer
./install.sh
```

Restart Claude Code for the statusline to appear.

## Manual installation

If you prefer to configure manually, add this to `~/.claude/settings.json`:

```json
{
  "statusLine": {
    "type": "command",
    "command": "/absolute/path/to/statusline.sh"
  }
}
```

Make the script executable:

```bash
chmod +x /absolute/path/to/statusline.sh
```

## Uninstall

```bash
./install.sh --remove
```

To also remove cached scan results:

```bash
rm -rf "${XDG_CACHE_HOME:-$HOME/.cache}/<tool>-statusline"
```

## Configuration

All options are controlled via environment variables. Set them in your shell profile
(`~/.bashrc`, `~/.zshrc`) or in `~/.claude/settings.json` under `"env"`.

| Variable | Default | Description |
|---|---|---|
| `TOOL_BIN` | `<tool>` | Path to the CLI binary |
| `TOOL_STATUSLINE_TTL` | `300` | Seconds between scans |
| `TOOL_SHOW_LOW` | `false` | Include low-severity issues in the display |
| `TOOL_SCAN_ARGS` | `""` | Extra arguments passed to the scan command |

### Examples

**Scan every 10 minutes:**
```bash
export TOOL_STATUSLINE_TTL=600
```

**Via `~/.claude/settings.json`:**
```json
{
  "statusLine": {
    "type": "command",
    "command": "/path/to/statusline.sh"
  },
  "env": {
    "TOOL_STATUSLINE_TTL": "600",
    "TOOL_SHOW_LOW": "true"
  }
}
```

## Troubleshooting

**Statusline shows "not authenticated"**
```bash
<check-auth-command>   # exit 0 = authenticated, non-zero = not
<do-auth-command>      # run ONLY if not authenticated
```
> Note: on some tools, re-running the auth command when already authenticated resets
> your credentials. Always check auth status before running the login command.

**Statusline shows "initializing..." forever**
```bash
# Run the scan manually to check for errors
<scan-command>

# Check the error log
cat "${XDG_CACHE_HOME:-$HOME/.cache}/<tool>-statusline/*.err"
```

**Tool not found in background scan**
On macOS with `nvm`, `fnm`, `rbenv`, or similar version managers, the tool may only
be in `PATH` in interactive shells. Background scans run in plain subshells and may
not inherit that `PATH`. Fix:
```bash
export TOOL_BIN=$(which <tool>)   # resolve once in your shell profile
```

**Results are stale**
```bash
rm -rf "${XDG_CACHE_HOME:-$HOME/.cache}/<tool>-statusline/"
```

**jq not found**
```bash
brew install jq          # macOS
sudo apt install jq      # Debian/Ubuntu
apk add jq               # Alpine
```

## Cache details

- **Location:** `~/.cache/<tool>-statusline/` (or `$XDG_CACHE_HOME/<tool>-statusline/`)
- **Files per project** (keyed by a hash of the git root path):
  - `{hash}.json` — last scan result
  - `{hash}.err` — stderr from the last scan (useful for auth debugging)
  - `{hash}.lock/` — atomic lock directory (present only while a scan is running)
  - `{hash}.noscan` — sentinel written when no supported project was found (exit code 3)
